There are two points along the ridge between Gangapurna and Roc Noir that have been called Tarke Kang. Before the HMG-Finn maps were published in the early 1990s, most maps referred to the 7168m point as Glacier Dome or Tarke Kang and the 7069m point was unnnamed. After the HMG-Finn maps publication, the 7069m point was called Tare Kang and the 7168m point was unnamed. Local maps now call the 7069m point Tarke Kang (Glacier Dome).

This becomes relevant because teams climbing from the south went to the 7168m point which we are now labelling as GLAC (Glacier Dome), while teams from the north went to the 7069m point which we are now labelling are TARS (or Tarke Kang Shar).

Leomann Sheet 1 shows the Raksha Urai Himal as a group 6 peaks (four peaks on one ridge with altitudes of 6345m, 6593m, 6628m and 6546m running north to south and an adjoining ridge with two peaks 6633m and 6371m). The 6633m peak is also called Dhaulasiri (and Dhaulagari on other maps).

The HMG-Finn map shows the Raksha Urai Himal as a group 6 peaks (four northern peaks on one ridge with altitudes of 6552m (aka Raksha Urai IV), 6609m (aka Raksha Urai III), 6420m (aka Raksha Urai II) and 6370m (aka Raksha Urai I) running north to south and a southern adjoining ridge with two peaks 6445m and 6638m). The Ministry of Tourism refers to the highest peak of northern group of four peaks as Raksha Urai and the highest peak of the southern group as Dhaulagari (or Dhaulasiri).
PSUMMITERS: Arnaud Clere, Catherine Couland, Gael Faroux, Keshab Raj Gurung

CHOY-811-01: Japanese used the SSW Ridge of LSAM (first ascent of the latter), it's clearly shown in the documentation put in the added piece.

CHOY-833-01: Italians and Nepalese used the same SSW Ridge of LSAM, shown by elements of their HD's account reported on the Schneider map [BC at south side of small lake north of Gyazumpa and south of point 5560m on Schneider map. (= on Nogzumpa Kang Glacier, SE to P6500m)], [3 members tried to climb to point 6515m (=route to E ridge, not SSW ridge), but no success (after Cho Oyu attempt)].

CHOY-873-04: Americans used first the LSAM SSW Ridge [Wally Berg confirmed it to me], then a line further left [Berg considers their 1987 second route option to be one of the variants of the yellow line shown on the aerial picture below].

CHOY-873-06: Eitel used the same second option as the Americans [doing the first ascent of this line to the plateau btw!].

CHOY-891-02: Kobler team used the same LSAM SSW Ridge [C1 below point 6500m on S Ridge].

CHOY-891-03: Koreans used the same LSAM SSW Ridge.[C1 same as Swiss].

CHOY-903-09: Russians used the same LSAM SSW Ridge. [C2 at point 6500m's on SW ridge].

CHOY-Winter 2021-2022: Nepalese used a similar line to the Americans' and Eitel's 1987 to reach the Nangpai Gosum Plateau.

In 2014, Jordi Corominas and Jordi Tosas summited LSAM only via SSW Ridge.
PSMTNOTE: Climbed by several team enroute to Cho Oyu (see Peak Notes)

There are two points along the ridge between Gangapurna and Roc Noir that have been called Tarke Kang. Before the HMG-Finn maps were published in the early 1990s, most maps referred to the 7168m point as Glacier Dome or Tarke Kang and the 7069m point was unnnamed. After the HMG-Finn maps publication, the 7069m point was called Tare Kang and the 7168m point was unnamed. Local maps now call the 7069m point Tarke Kang (Glacier Dome).

This becomes relevant because teams climbing from the south went to the 7168m point which we are now labelling as GLAC (Glacier Dome), while teams from the north went to the 7069m point which we are now labelling are TARS (or Tarke Kang Shar).
PSUMMITERS: Claudio Schranz, Marco Roncaglioni, Gianfranco Tagliaferri, Gombu Sherpa
